nshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Nasu Onsen Shrine|ja|那須温泉神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tochigi Prefecture, {{ill|Nasu District|ja|那須郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nasu|ja|那須町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nasu Onsen|ja|那須温泉郷|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Famous for the {{ill|Sessho-seki|ja|殺生石|12=draft|12=draft}}. The "Nasu Yumoto Daijingū" mentioned in the {{ill|Heike Monogatari|ja|平家物語|12=draft|12=draft}} is said to refer to this shrine. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Nikkō)|ja|温泉神社 (日光市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tochigi Prefecture, {{ill|Nikkō|ja|日光市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kinugawa Onsen|ja|鬼怒川温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Yumae Shrine|ja|湯前神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Atami|ja|熱海市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Atami Onsen|ja|熱海温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Izuyama Shrine|ja|射山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tsu|ja|津市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sakakibara Onsen|ja|榊原温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Yusen Shrine (Kobe)|ja|湯泉神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kobe|ja|神戸市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kita-ku (Kobe)|ja|北区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Sometimes referred to as "Onsen Shrine." Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto, and Kumano-Kusumi-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Shisho Shrine (Toyooka)|ja|四所神社 (豊岡市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Hyōgo Prefecture, {{ill|Toyooka|ja|豊岡市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kinosaki Onsen|ja|城崎温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Enshrines Yuyama-no-Kami (湯山主神) and others. It is said that Dōchi, who visited this shrine, was divinely inspired to open the public bath "Mandarayu." * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Shirahama)|ja|温泉神社 (白浜町)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nishimuro District|ja|西牟婁郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shirahama|ja|白浜町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nanki Shirahama Onsen|ja|南紀白浜温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Yumoto Shrine|ja|湯本神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Maniwa|ja|真庭市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yubara Onsen|ja|湯原温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - The location was formerly called Yubara, but upon Maniwa City's establishment, it was renamed Yubara Onsen. * {{ill|Miyu Shrine|ja|御湯神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tottori Prefecture|ja|鳥取県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwami District|ja|岩美郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwami|ja|岩美町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwai Onsen|ja|岩井温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Yakami-hime-no-Mikoto, Miino-Kami, and Sarutahiko-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Tamatsukuri Shrine|ja|玉作湯神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shimane Prefecture|ja|島根県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Matsue|ja|松江市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tamatsukuri Onsen|ja|玉造温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Kushiakarutama-no-Kami, Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Yu Shrine (Dōgo Onsen)|ja|湯神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ehime Prefecture|ja|愛媛県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Matsuyama|ja|松山市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Dōgo Onsen|ja|道後温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Higashidōgo Shrine|ja|東道後神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Ehime Prefecture, Matsuyama, {{ill|Higashidōgo Onsen|ja|東道後温泉郷|12=draft|12=draft}}) - A subordinate shrine of {{ill|Hio Hachiman Shrine|ja|日尾八幡神社|12=draft|12=draft}}. Enshrines Amenominakanushi-no-Kami, Amaterasu-Ōmikami, and Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Beppu)|ja|温泉神社 (別府市青山町)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Ōita Prefecture|ja|大分県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Beppu|ja|別府市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Beppu Onsen|ja|別府温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Founded during the Taishō period. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto, and others. Currently merged into {{ill|Hachiman Asami Shrine|ja|八幡朝見神社|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Beppu Tetsuwana)|ja|温泉神社 (別府市鉄輪)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Ōita Prefecture, Beppu, {{ill|Tetsuwana Onsen|ja|鉄輪温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Hinokuma Hime Shrine|ja|火男火売神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Ōita Prefecture, Beppu, Tetsuwana Onsen) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Hinokagutsuchi-no-Mikoto and Hiyakehayahime-no-Mikoto. It is said that {{ill|Ippen|ja|一遍|12=draft|12=draft}} Shōnin was inspired by this shrine, called Tsurumi Gongen, to create a stone steam bath (mushi-yu). "Hayami no Yu," a hot spring flowing from the base of the sacred Tsurumidake mountain, is believed to have been directed to Dōgo Onsen by Ōkuninushi-no-Mikoto through an underwater channel. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Unzen)|ja|温泉神社 (雲仙市)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Unzen|ja|雲仙市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Obama Onsen|ja|小浜町雲仙|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Unzen Onsen|ja|雲仙温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - A Kokusai-mizai-sha. Dedicated to the deity of Tsukushi Island (modern {{ill|Kyūshū|ja|九州|12=draft|12=draft}}), represented in the form of "Isshin Shimen" (a single body with four faces). The shrine is also known as "Shimen-gū." The name "Unzen" derives from the reading of 温泉 (onsen), but the shrine is pronounced as written: "Onsen Jinja." Over a dozen branch shrines of the same name exist within the {{ill|Shimabara Peninsula|ja|島原半島|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Shimabara)|ja|温泉神社 (島原市亀の甲町)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, {{ill|Shimabara|ja|島原市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kamenokō-chō) * {{ill|Onsen Kumano Shrine|ja|温泉熊野神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, Shimabara) * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Unzen Kunimi)|ja|温泉神社 (雲仙市国見町多比良丁)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, Unzen, Kunimi-machi Tabirachō) * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Unzen Azuma)|ja|温泉神社 (雲仙市吾妻町布江名)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, Unzen, Azuma-machi Fuenami)