{{Otheruses|'''Overview of Shrines Related to Hot Springs'''|'''Individual Shrines Named Onsen Shrine'''|温泉神社 (曖昧さ回避)}} '''Onsen Shrine''' (温泉神社, Onsen Jinja) refers to a type of {{ill|shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, or a commonly used name, associated with {{ill|onsen|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|1=Onsen|12=draft|12=draft}} (hot springs).
== Overview == An Onsen Shrine is a shrine connected to or dedicated to hot springs. Such shrines are found across Japan, primarily in hot spring areas.
Japan's landscape, intersected by volcanic zones, is abundant in hot springs. Since ancient times, hot springs have been revered as the abodes of deities, known as "Hot Spring Deities" or "Onsen Kami." Shrines dedicated to these deities are referred to as "Yugami Shrines" or "Onsen Shrines." Many ancient hot springs are traditionally associated with deities such as {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少彦名神|12=draft|12=draft}}, who are often enshrined as Onsen Kami.
According to the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|12=draft|12=draft}}, there are three shrines specifically named "Onsen Shrine," along with others such as "Onsen Stone Shrine," "Hot Spring Shrine," "Yugami Shrine," "Miyu Shrine," and "Tamakusuyugami Shrine," making a total of ten shrines related to hot springs listed as {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Shrines Related to Hot Springs Across Japan ==
* {{ill|Onsen Ishi Shrine|ja|温泉石神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Miyagi Prefecture|ja|宮城県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōsaki|ja|大崎市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kawatabi Onsen|ja|川渡温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}}. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Ōsaki)|ja|温泉神社 (大崎市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Miyagi Prefecture, Ōsaki, {{ill|Naruko Onsen|ja|鳴子温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Yuzusame Shrine|ja|由豆佐売神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Yamagata Prefecture|ja|山形県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tsuruoka|ja|鶴岡市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yutagawa Onsen|ja|湯田川温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Mizokuihime-no-Mikoto, Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Yusen Shrine (Kōriyama)|ja|湯泉神社 (郡山市)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kōriyama|ja|郡山市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Bandai-Atami Onsen|ja|磐梯熱海温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Enshrines Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto, among others. Divinity of hot springs brought from Izu by the {{ill|Azumi Itō Clan|ja|安積伊東氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Iwaki)|ja|温泉神社 (いわき市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Fukushima Prefecture, {{ill|Iwaki|ja|いわき市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwaki Yumoto Onsen|ja|いわき湯本温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, {{ill|Kotoshironushi-no-Kami|ja|事代主命|12=draft|12=draft}}, and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Ōtawara)|ja|温泉神社 (大田原市中野内)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tochigi Prefecture|ja|栃木県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōtawara|ja|大田原市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kurobane Onsen|ja|黒羽温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto, and others. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Nasushiobara)|ja|温泉神社 (那須塩原市湯本塩原)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tochigi Prefecture, {{ill|Nasushiobara|ja|那須塩原市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shiobara Onsen|ja|塩原温泉郷|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Nasu Onsen Shrine|ja|那須温泉神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tochigi Prefecture, {{ill|Nasu District|ja|那須郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nasu|ja|那須町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nasu Onsen|ja|那須温泉郷|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Famous for the {{ill|Sessho-seki|ja|殺生石|12=draft|12=draft}}. The "Nasu Yumoto Daijingū" mentioned in the {{ill|Heike Monogatari|ja|平家物語|12=draft|12=draft}} is said to refer to this shrine. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Nikkō)|ja|温泉神社 (日光市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Tochigi Prefecture, {{ill|Nikkō|ja|日光市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kinugawa Onsen|ja|鬼怒川温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) * {{ill|Yumae Shrine|ja|湯前神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Atami|ja|熱海市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Atami Onsen|ja|熱海温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Izuyama Shrine|ja|射山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tsu|ja|津市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sakakibara Onsen|ja|榊原温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Yusen Shrine (Kobe)|ja|湯泉神社|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kobe|ja|神戸市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kita-ku (Kobe)|ja|北区|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Arima Onsen|ja|有馬温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Shikinai-sha. Sometimes referred to as "Onsen Shrine." Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto, and Kumano-Kusumi-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Shisho Shrine (Toyooka)|ja|四所神社 (豊岡市)|12=draft|12=draft}} (Hyōgo Prefecture, {{ill|Toyooka|ja|豊岡市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kinosaki Onsen|ja|城崎温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) - Enshrines Yuyama-no-Kami (湯山主神) and others. It is said that Dōchi, who visited this shrine, was divinely inspired to open the public bath "Mandarayu." * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Shirahama)|ja|温泉神社 (白浜町)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Wakaya