ecture]], [[:en:Iwami District, Tottori|Iwami District]], [[:en:Iwami, Tottori|Iwami]], {{ill|Iwai Onsen|ja|岩井温泉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwai Onsen|qq=}}) - Shikinaisha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Yakami-hime-no-Mikoto, Miino-Kami, and Sarutahiko-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Tamatsukuri Shrine|ja|玉作湯神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamatsukuri Shrine|qq=}} ([[:en:Shimane Prefecture|Shimane Prefecture]], [[:en:Matsue|Matsue]], [[:en:Tamatsukuri Onsen|Tamatsukuri Onsen]]) - Shikinaisha. Enshrines Kushiakarutama-no-Kami, Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Yu Shrine|lt=Yu Shrine|lt=Yu Shrine (Dōgo Onsen)|ja|湯神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yu Shrine (Dōgo Onsen)|qq=}} ([[:en:Ehime Prefecture|Ehime Prefecture]], [[:en:Matsuyama|Matsuyama]], [[:en:Dōgo Onsen|Dōgo Onsen]]) - Shikinaisha. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Higashidōgo Shrine|ja|東道後神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashidōgo Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 日尾八幡神社}} (Ehime Prefecture, Matsuyama, {{ill|Higashidōgo Onsen|ja|東道後温泉郷|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashidōgo Onsen|qq=}}) - A subordinate shrine of {{ill|Hio Hachiman Shrine|ja|日尾八幡神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hio Hachiman Shrine|qq=}}. Enshrines Amenominakanushi-no-Kami, Amaterasu-Ōmikami, and Tsukuyomi-no-Mikoto. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Beppu)|ja|温泉神社 (別府市青山町)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Shrine (Beppu)|qq=}} ([[:en:Ōita Prefecture|Ōita Prefecture]], [[:en:Beppu|Beppu]], [[:en:Beppu Onsen|Beppu Onsen]]) - Founded during the Taishō period. Enshrines Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto, Sukunabikona-no-Mikoto, and others. Currently merged into {{ill|Hachiman Asami Shrine|ja|八幡朝見神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiman Asami Shrine|qq=}}. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Beppu Tetsuwana)|ja|温泉神社 (別府市鉄輪)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Shrine (Beppu Tetsuwana)|qq=}} (Ōita Prefecture, Beppu, {{ill|Tetsuwana Onsen|ja|鉄輪温泉|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tetsuwana Onsen|qq=}}) * {{ill|Hinokuma Hime Shrine|ja|火男火売神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hinokuma Hime Shrine|qq=}} (Ōita Prefecture, Beppu, Tetsuwana Onsen) - Shikinaisha. Enshrines Hinokagutsuchi-no-Mikoto and Hiyakehayahime-no-Mikoto. It is said that [[:en:Ippen|Ippen]] Shōnin was inspired by this shrine, called Tsurumi Gongen, to create a stone steam bath (mushi-yu). "Hayami no Yu," a hot spring flowing from the base of the sacred Tsurumidake mountain, is believed to have been directed to Dōgo Onsen by Ōkuninushi-no-Mikoto through an underwater channel. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Unzen)|ja|温泉神社 (雲仙市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Shrine (Unzen)|qq=}} ([[:en:Nagasaki Prefecture|Nagasaki Prefecture]], [[:en:Unzen, Nagasaki|Unzen]], {{ill|Obama Onsen|ja|小浜町雲仙|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Obama Onsen|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, [[:en:Unzen Onsen|Unzen Onsen]]) - A Kokusai-mizai-sha. Dedicated to the deity of Tsukushi Island (modern [[:en:Kyushu|Kyūshū]]), represented in the form of "Isshin Shimen" (a single body with four faces). The shrine is also known as "Shimen-gū." The name "Unzen" derives from the reading of 温泉 (onsen), but the shrine is pronounced as written: "Onsen Jinja." Over a dozen branch shrines of the same name exist within the [[:en:Shimabara Peninsula|Shimabara Peninsula]]. * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Shimabara)|ja|温泉神社 (島原市亀の甲町)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Shrine (Shimabara)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, [[:en:Shimabara, Nagasaki|Shimabara]], Kamenokō-chō) * {{ill|Onsen Kumano Shrine|ja|温泉熊野神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Kumano Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, Shimabara) * {{ill|Onsen Shrine (Unzen Kunimi)|ja|温泉神社 (雲仙市国見町多比良丁)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen Shrine (Unzen Kunimi)|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Nagasaki Prefecture, Unzen, Kunimi-machi Tabirachō) * {{ill|Onsen Shrine 